children.subject: Can't wait to take a class with you again Miki!
Is EE120 prereq for this or EE16AB is sufficient?

I assume knowledge of EE120 material. 

While folks have taken the class without it, it was not always so successful.
Hi! Interested in taking this class in future semesters (I believe I need to take EE 120 first). Is this class only offered in the spring?

With mixed feelings.... it will. 

But I really not enjoy teaching in front of 25% of the class.
Will there be a final exam in addition to the final project?

I took 120 with Babak in Fall 2017, and 123 last semester. I'd say 123 is significantly higher workload - the psets are comparable but the labs take a decent amount of time, and the final project adds up at the end of the semester. However, it's a pretty constant and doable load.
Agree with Dinesh - it's *a lot* more work than Babak's 120, mainly due to the labs, which are awesome, but take a lot of time.
Do you guys think EE 120 with CS 61B and EE 16B is doable?

No, but not because of the workload. The workload would be fine in isolation, but you want 16B before 120, or the entire context for 120 won’t make much sense, and plus you need the familiarity with complex numbers 16B gives you first. Don’t take 120 without 16B.
Would going over 16B webcast lectures during the winter break be enough? I read somewhere else that Babak kinda start from the ground up.
I know from taking 120 rn that you will be fine without 16B. Just have mathematical maturity, especially with complex numbers
How is the courseload compared to Babak's current 120 class.

history.content:
Take EE123 "Digital Signal Processing" this Spring!
Signals rule our world. Sensor data is constantly being captured, processed, compressed, stored and analyzed. DSP has become the swiss army knife of tools every engineer and scientist should know. The class covers transform tools such as spectral analysis and wavelets to find features in data, processing techniques such as filter design, interpolation and resampling, fast computation algorithms such as multi-rate processing and FFT as well as advanced topics which include compressive sensing and tomography. The cream of the crop are the labs in which students get experience in real-world signal processing. These include making your computer into a sonar, labs with software radio to decode airplane traffic and play FM station and finally experimentation with digital communication. Labs are implemented using Python on Raspberry Pi miniatured computers. All students will end up with an amateur radio license as well.
 
 
Take a look at previous semester material and final project videos:
https://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~ee123/sp18/projectVideos.html
-- Miki
